args:
The party finally settles things with Nedrick,
but his rage still burns. To calm his ire,
Audric reveals that he is, in fact, Aurelius,
which convinces Nedrick to finally surrender
and join their cause.
We're ending this, Nedrick. There's no\npoint in our fighting any longer.
You don't have any strength left.
And no wonder, considering how often\nwe've fought and how many times you\ncalled upon Bahamut's power.
You are wounded, weary, and spent.\nIf we continue, you will likely perish.
No. We need your strength—we have from\nthe very beginning. Fighting you to the\ndeath serves no purpose.
You... You have always been so soft,\nand I CANNOT STAND IT!
Get out of my damn way!
Enough, Nedrick.\nYou know this is meaningless.
There is no need for you to shoulder the\npact with Bahamut and the fate of the\nentire world alone.

Or can you just not bring yourself to
forgive the one who was given all that
ought to have been yours by right?
To forgive {player_name}?
Do not belittle me so! My goals are far\nbeyond such pettiness!
There is no shame in fighting for\nsmall goals, Nedrick.
The same powerless people you seek to\nsave have only small goals, yet fight with\nall they have for them.
Why would you deny that idea?
If you feel any enmity toward\n{player_name}...
Then direct your hate to me, for I am\nthe one who should bear it.
My true name is Aurelius, and I am the\ndamn fool of a king who caused the\ndownfall of Alberia.
I knew it! I knew you're our father!\nBut then, what of your appearance?

No, dear Chelle. I am not your father.
I am an Aurelius from another world,
one where the flow of time has branched
off in a very different direction.

The Aurelius of this world died in battle
with the Other—a battle I survived.
As my struggles continued, I became
the man you now see before you.
So are you from the same different world\nas Zena, or a DIFFERENT different world?
No. This Zena—this Zethia—is from yet\nanother world. Sadly, my Zethia was slain\nby the Other.
My foolish actions led my world down\nthe path to ruination.
And when I came to this world, I decided\nto make penance for what I had done.
More than anything, I am here to give\nyou the many things I stole away.
In other words, you are not Aurelius at all,\nbut a different man. I feel nothing for you.
It's true that I am not the Aurelius of this\nworld—but since I came here, I have\nexperienced his memories in many ways.
That's right, my father's letter!\nHe wrote that he left his feelings in the\nSacred Tree...

Correct. And while I know not if it was
coincidence or something else that guided
me to this place, it is here that I received
Aurelius's memories.
I became one with his memories—\nand with his heart. Thus, it is accurate\nto say I am both Audric AND Aurelius.
So the things you claimed\nmy father said...
They were his true feelings for you.
Then thank you again for telling them\nto me, Audric. ...Er, Father?
And now, Nedrick, I would have you hear\nhis thoughts about yourself.
I have little interest in what a dead man\nthinks of the child he tossed aside.
It was not until some considerable time\nlater that Aurelius learned of the survival\nof the true seventh scion—you, Nedrick.
He thought long and hard about confessing\neverything and welcoming you as a prince.
But he worried what it would mean\nfor {player_name}, who lived\nin your place.

Though he fretted over it without pause,
he could reach no good conclusion,
and soon he began to view himself as
a vile and useless parent.
Yet I feel neither hate nor disappointment,\nfor I had no expectations for Aurelius to\nbegin with.
But though he was ever ashamed to look\nyou in the eye, there remained something\nhe had to do for you.
When Aurelius learned that Nedrick lived,\nhe also discovered that he had been made\nBahamut's vessel.
After that, he bent his will to finding a way\nof freeing Nedrick from this burden.
In the process, he found the forbidden\ntechnique which also saved Zethia earlier.
But as an answer eluded him, he grew\ndesperate—and in that desperation, he\nturned to something he ought never have.
THAT'S why he went to the Binding Ruins?!
He went there for the Sacred Shard,\nof course, but at the same time he was\nseeking a way to counter Bahamut.
Then you claim our Father awakening\nMorsayati was no accident?
So at the same time I headed for the\nDragon Choosing, Father went to the\nBinding Ruins to try to save Nedrick?
Was so much misery ever caused by the\nfoolish choices of a single man?
Aurelius spoke of this to no one, and did\nnot even seek the aid of his old friends\nFinlorda and Gatov.
Why would he not come to me before\ncasting his lot with the Other?
Because he was afraid of showing you\nhis weak and ugly sides.
He feared he would disappoint those he\ntrusted, and that they would abandon him.
He need not have worried about such,\nespecially considering that my own\nfather is far weaker and uglier.
In the end, being afraid to trust was\nthe start of all this misery.
So do not repeat my mistake, Nedrick!\nYou must not fear trusting in others!
The world is not so light that the burden\nof it can be borne by a single person.
Which is exactly why I cannot entrust\nsuch a burden to others!
Who can carry the world on their back?!\nWho can I ask to take on such a task?!

Do not be afraid, Nedrick. Merely believe.
If you do, I am certain those who are able
to stand with you and bear these burdens
will make themselves known.
I swear this on the name of Alberius\nand all the regents of Alberia!

Even without me, it would seem you are
capable of finding the power to resist
Bahamut. I am willing to leave the pact
with Zethia for now.
I will bear it with all care.
It does indeed. Thank you, all of you—\nand apologies again for all the trouble\nI have caused.
With this, my part in this story\ncomes to an end.
Don't be daft. You've got your children to...\nAurelius? Aurelius, what's happening\nto your body?!
